Introduction¶

Female Labour Participation Rates (FLPR) measure the percentages of the working female population in relation to the country's total female population. Several sources verify that female labour force participation are substantially lower than male labour participation almost everywhere in the world (ILO, World Bank). Regardless of the male labour force participation, the percentage of women working can vary significantly across the globe.

Throughout the report I will investigate female labour participation geographically and how it may have changed over time. Further, I'm going to analyse to what extend a country's economic situation may determine if women engage in the labour market.

Properties Female Labour Participation Rates (FLPR)¶

Source: Gapminder, provided by International Labour Organization (ilostat)

Description
Central to this report are labour force participation rates of females aged over 15 years in countries around the globe. It states the percentage of the working female population in relation to the country's total female population. The FLPR counts all working females or females who are actively looking for labour. That includes self-employed and unemployed females. FLPRs are likely to be underestimated as 'female' work (e.g. care work) is often not considered as employment. https://www.ilo.org/ilostat-files/Documents/description_LFPR_EN.pdf

Properties
The female labour particpation dataset contains data of 179 countries over the years 1990 to 2017 (28 years). The country column comes in the data format of a string and the years columns state the FLPR in the form of a float. ILO provides us with imputed estimate values. Hence, there are no null values.

Gross National Income per Capita (GNI)¶

Source: Gapminder, provided by World Bank

Description
To evaluate the world economy by country, I'm investigating the Gross National Incomes of countries (GNI), provided by the World Bank. It measures the country's income per capita. The GNI is closely related to the GDP. In contrast to the GDP, it includes all compensations paid to domestic residents by foreign businesses. Subsidies and paid compensations to overseas residents are subtracted. Product and income taxes are also included in the GNI. The GNI is calculated in national currency and converted to U.S. dollars at official exchange rates. The data set uses the 'Atlas method' to smooth out fluctuations in prices and exchange rates. https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NY.GNP.PCAP.CD

Properties
We got GNI values by country for the years 1962 to 2017. The data of a country is of type string and the GNI comes as a float, which makes up for 56 years. Many rows contain null values.

The data wrangling showed the data comes already in appropriate data formats. We got recorded yearly data without gaps. The smallest number of recorded countries is the FLPR data containing 178 countries. Since there are currently 195 countries in the world, our dataset covers the great majority of the globe. Nevertheless, there are four key findings, I have to pay attention to throughout the following data cleaning process.

Time frame
The data wrangling uncovered the years 1991 to 2017 to be in common across all datasets. It makes sense to focus on the time frame of common data, so I'm going to drop values of earlier or later years.

Countries
I noticed that some of the datasets include different countries than others. Throughout the analysis I want to make sure to compare a set of matching countries. Throughout the cleaning, I will drop rows containing non-matching countries. The naming/spelling of some countries differs to some extend in the df_countries containing data from Wikimedia and the Gampminder dataframes. Throughout the cleaning/analysis, I renamed country names in the countries_by_category.csv file directly.

Null values in GNI data
The GNI dataset contains quite a significant amount of null values. Especially the early years seem to be quite incomplete. The possible reasons for missing data: countries may have not existed, were re-formed or annexed. Also, economic data may have not been recorded or shared with the world bank. However, since the 1990s the dataset's null values seem to be less missing at random, but for geographical or political reasons.

Analysis of the GNI development over the years shows a linear change for most of the countries. Since previously existing countries are not part of the list, yet the geographic area existed, I decided to fill null values using linear interpolation. For example, Bosnia Herzegovina shows recorded data only since the mid '90s. The previously existing Yugoslavia is not part of the data set anymore. Not counting in the geographic area would have underestimated the GNI significantly.

Merging and table format
The data currently comes in separate files. To analyse variables and their possible dependencies, we can make our lives easier by combining the data into a common dataframe. The current formatting of our data tables follows the pattern of having the years as column labels. Since, we are analysing the same time frame and are interested in different variables, it makes sense to shift years into rows. Instead of year labels, we will now have variable names (e.g. FLPR, GNI) as columns.

Data Cleaning¶

Cleaning GNI¶

The GNI data contains values over the period of 1962 to 2017. Since, we are only interested in the years 1991 to 2017, we drop data of earlier years. Even after removing, we find many null values. As explained above, we are going to perform linear interpolation to fill in missing values.

Create combined dataframes¶

To analysis and plot data, it makes sense to change the table formatting and combine data in common tables. To keep the dataframes neat, I will create two dataframes: the first dataframe will combine FLPR and GNI data. To help us analyse geographic data, I'm assigning a world region and their development status to every country. I can simply do this by merging df_countries with our data. The second dataframe will comprise employment data by sector.

All datasets are currently formatted with the recorded years as separate columns. However, this format turns out to be unhandy, if we want to plot our data. Instead, we want all years in one column and the variables we are analysing in the form of columns.

In [25]:
# pivot the tables from wide format to long format
df_serv = pd.melt(df_serv, id_vars=["country"], var_name='year', value_name="service")
df_ind = pd.melt(df_ind, id_vars=["country"], var_name='year', value_name="industry")
df_agr = pd.melt(df_agr, id_vars=["country"], var_name='year', value_name="agriculture")
df_flpr = pd.melt(df_flpr, id_vars=["country"], var_name='year', value_name="flpr")
df_gni = pd.melt(df_gni, id_vars=["country"], var_name='year', value_name="gni")

We should have 3 columns now: 'country', 'year' and the respective variable's name. Country and year shall remain a string, while the investigated variable comes in form of a number (float or int).

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Does any region's female labour force participation outperform other regions?¶

I am going to analyse to what extend women participate in employed work around the globe. To get an impression how female employment participation is distributed, I am going to explore the Female Labour Force Participation Rate geographically. How is female employment participation distributed across the world's regions? I am going to investigate where we typically find countries with high FLPRs and where in the world do women engage less in the labour market. Part of the analysis is to find out how female labour participation changed over time. Are there world regions which were faced with bigger changes compared to other regions?

In [32]:
# Let's take a look on the FLPR

Over the period of 1991 to 2017, we observed Labour Force Participation Rates in 176 countries ranging from 6% to 90.3%. Meaning, there were countries with a minmum of 6% of all adult women engaging in the labour market and other countries with up to 90% of all adult women engaging in employment. The global average female labour participation rate over the years 1991 to 2017 was 50.4%.

Let's visualize how the global FLPR changed over time. I am going to plot line graphs and box plots of the average female labour participation over the time. By grouping our data geographically, we can observe patterns across continental regions of the globe.

The above line graphs picture mean female labour participation rates over the period of 1991 to 2017. The highlighted graph describes the global mean, the other graphs show the mean FLPRs of the Asia & Pacific, Europe, Arab States, Africa, South/Latin America and North America.

We observe a modest increase of the global average FLPR over the time period of 1991 to 2017. In 1991 the mean FLPR was at 48.46%. By 2017 it had risen to 52.06% with a slight max. of 52.06% in the year 2016. Close to the global mean FLPR are Europe and Asian & Pacific States. The plot of South/Latin America shows a stronger increase than the average. In the early 90s South Americas FLPRs were at a bit more than 40%. By the mid 2000s, the FLPRs had risen above the levels of the global mean and are in 2017 at roughly 50%.

The far lowest mean FLPRs occur in Arab States. As a matter of fact, over the years we observe a relatively strong growth. Yet the Arab States average below 30%.

North America's female employment participation is above the global average. However, since 2008/2009 we also observe the strongest recession of all regions.

African women's employment participation outweighs by far other world regions with a rate at above 60%.

While the mean labour participation rates are interesting to observe global patterns, they don't tell us much about how divers the FLP rates across each world regions are. To visualize their diversity, we are going to use boxplot they year 2017.

# Formula to calculate growth rates of FLPR compared to 1991. 
def calc_growth(row, col):
    val_latest = row[col]
    val_1991 = df_comb.query('(country ==@row.country) & (year == "1991")').iloc[0][col]
    change_rate = ((val_latest - val_1991) / val_latest) * 100
    return change_rate

# Create new column 'flpr_change' with each cell containing the growth compared to 1991 
df_comb_2017['flpr_change'] = df_comb_2017.apply(lambda row: calc_growth(row, 'flpr'), axis=1)

Investigating growth rates of female labour force participation, we find one outstanding area: Arab States. They show the longest tails and highest interquartile ranges for both: positive and negative development. The difference towards other regions is especially significant at decreasing growth rates. Positive growth is much stronger across all regions, except in Arab States. After the Arab States, South America shows the second highest growth rates. North America's median growth was the lowest at about 5%.

Is the FLPR different in the Global North and Global South?
We noticed the level of female labour participation rates is roughly connected to world regions. Taking a closer look at specific world regions may result in very diverse female labour participation rates. This is especially true for Asian & Pacific states. One factor that might influence the FLPR is the political and socio-economic region of a country. We can divide the world in Global North for the developed world and Global South for the developing world. To visualize the connection, we are going to use a boxplot.

Both groups Global North and Global South have their median on one level at slightly above 50%. Compared to the Global North, the Global South has a longer interquartile range and longer tails with a few outliers in the low percentage FLPR. It shows extremes to occur rather in the Global South. The developed world tends to have rather mediocre female labour participation rates.

As Global North and Global South are a political and socio-economic description of the world, I suspect the economic situation of a country could drive female employment participation. Below, I am going to further investigate the relationship.

Does a country's economic situation drive female employment participation?¶

To find out the relationship between female employment participation and the economic situation of a country, I will analyse two factors. First, the Gross National Income (GNI) of a country and second the labour market's industry distribution.

The GNI describes the total domestic and foreign output of all residents of a country. It is a measure to helps us compare the economic activities across regions. Using the GNI, I am going to investigate whether there is a pattern of poor or rich countries having higher or lower female participation rates.

I am going to describe a country's industry by analysing the distribution of its economic sectors: service, agriculture and industry. The aim is to examine if there a correlation between female employment participation and a dominant economic sector? Is the type of work women engage in connected to a regions overall female labour participation?

Does poor and rich country's female labour participation rates perform differently?

Conclusions¶

Does any region's female labour force participation outperform other regions?¶

Over the period of 1991 to 2017, we observed female labour force participation rates in 176 countries ranging from 6% to 90.3%. To observe patterns across regions, we segmented our country data into the world regions Asia & Pacific, South/Latin America, North America, Europe, Africa and Arab States. We observe a slow increase of the global average FLPRs. In 1991, the mean FLPR was at 48.5%. By 2017, it had risen to 52.1%.

We observed trends of female participation rates that are particular to a world region. However, the variation of female labour participation rates may vary strongly within one world region.

African countries tend to have the highest mean female labour force participation. Among the most extreme FLPRs, we mostly find African states and a few Asian & Pacific States. In 2017, Rwanda reached the top FLPR of 86%, followed by Madagascar (83.6%) and Nepal (82.7%).

Female labour particpation rates of Arab States underperform significantly. We find the lowest rates mostly in Arab States. In 2017, Yemen had the lowest rate at 6%, followed by Syria (11.9%) and Jordan (14%). Among the lowest rates is also a noticeable number of Southwest-Asian states like Iran, Afghanistan and Pakistan.

The strongest growth of FLPR was observed in Iraq. By 2017, it had increased by 56.3%. On the other hand, Yemen (-180%) and Syria (-89.91%) experienced dramatic decreased female labour participation rates.

The growth rates of Arab States outperformed other regions in both directions. They have significant occurrences of both, extremely positive and negative growth rates. North America was significant in the respect of its median growth. As a region, it was comparatively low at about 5%. We even observe a slightly negative trend since the mid 2000s.

If we divide the world by their developmental status of Global North and Global South, we find the Global South to be more heterogeneous in terms of their FLPRs. Extremes tend to occur rather in the Global South. The developed world tends to have rather mediocre female labour participation rates.

Does a country's economic situation drive female employment participation?¶

To investigate the economic situation of a country and its female labour participation, we explored the country's gross national incomes and their economic sectors.

Compared to the global FLPR, the GNI shows a more significant growth from 1991 to 2017. The global GNI more than doubled in 27 years. We observed a strong increase in the early 2000s until the year 2014, thereafter it declines. The global FLPR however shows a constant, relatively slow positive trend. The global relationship of these factors seems to be rather weak if any.

Comparing female labour participation rates against a country's economic output directly, results in u-shaped curve. In very poor countries women tend to participate at high levels in employment. The average FLPR drops for low income and moderately high income countries to mostly very low and low rates. However, the mean FLPRs are slightly increasing at moderately high GNI rates. In rich countries the trend changes towards reversed direction. Country's of moderately high female labour participation outweigh lower rated countries. Yet, rich country's FLPRs don't reach high rates like the poorest countries.

We observe strong variations of FLP rates within different income groups. Especially in very low and low income countries the FLPRs are not consistent at country level. For example, Afghanistan and Cambodia are both very poor countries. Yet, Afghanistan has a rate of 19.5%, while Cambodia a rate of 80.9%. The data suggests the possibility of additional socio-economic, political or cultural factors that drive the degree to which women participate in employment.

One other factor could be the type of work that is in demand in an economy. We found out that country's of high female labour participation typically have an unusually dominant agriculture sector (51.7%) compared to service and industry sectors. In all other country's from low to moderately high female labour participation, agricultural employment has a relatively low importance. With rates at 60.3 to 75.5% the service sector outweighs by far the agricultural sector.

In this report we found out that female labour participation varies across the globe significantly. There are patterns of the percentages of female labour participation across regions and according to a country's economy. However, the correlation with the strength of an economy is not straightforward in any case. It is especially insignificant for low to moderately high income countries. There are divergent FLPRs within regions and across different economic outputs. In this respect, we are inspired to ask what other socio-economic, political or cultural factors may drive female labour participation.

We have to handle the above results with caution. According to ilostat, female labour participation has been poorly measured and widely underestimated. On the one hand, female work is often not considered as employment. On the other hand, often men report on behalf of women when responding to surveys. In this respect, we expect the data to be biased towards a male view on employment. Another fact that may bias our findings are divergent population numbers of countries. China with 683 million women has the same weight as Montenegro with a population of only 319,000 women. We may expect that the FLPR within a large country like China may vary internally. As we've seen in our research above, this reports findings hold true on a country level, yet may change if we want to describe the situation of women in absolute population numbers.
